I like all that's been said so far about things.  I just wanted to add something else- I think that attitude goes a long way.  I wanted to take the opportunity to make everyone aware of how people's anxiety management in Kedge Keep can either help or hurt the entire action.<br>
<br>
As the assistant raid leader for this, I can tell you that getting /tells from non-group leaders asking me superficial and unimportant questions (i.e.&quot;why are we doing this?&quot;) definitely distracted me from attending to the seven different group leaders, as well as guild officers, with whom I was in constant communication.  I don't mean to trivialize everyone's concerns-- nobody's going to be happy 100% of the time, and I recognize that.  When I say &quot;superficial and unimportant&quot;, I'm referring to statements that are more comment based, &quot;you shouldn't have done that&quot; (which is not only vague but out of place), as well as those that do not directly benefit the raid.  These types of comments and questions are quite normal to make during many raids-- but kedge is different.  It is crucial that raid leaders, group leaders, and group members maintain maximum focus and attention in Kedge.  <br>
<br>
I propose requring everyone to disable guildchat once they are in the zone, as well- I noticed several group members chatting away in guildchat-- some of these were people that we ended up waiting for at various points during the raid.  If guild help is needed, it will be the raid leader's responsibility to solicit non-raid guild members for that help.   <br>
<br>
    Most of us, I'm sure, respond to /tells by hitting, &quot;R&quot;, and this can be particularly useful when the person you are responding to has a very long name.  I was using this strategy on the raid, to respond extremely fast and immediately to group leader and guild officer concerns, so that each group would know what to do next, and when to do it (while keeping in mind that the next room spawn may be perhaps 50 seconds away).<br>
<br>
    However, since one or two group members decided to /tell me what they were thinking every step of the way.. &quot;why are we doing this, we should do this, we should do that&quot;... the /tell floods definitely interrupted my rhythm of keeping track of everyone at all times.  I had to then re-type the group leader's name, respond to that person... then respond efficiently to the non-leader's innappropriate comments to keep morale up and be a respectful leader.<br>
  During this 15 second interval, I have a back-log of about 4 or 5 other /tells from the appropriate people, that could have been responded to immediately (many of them needed to be responded to immediately)-- this, I guarantee you, was another reason why we seemed to be &quot;idle&quot; for a minute or so after a fight ended and rezzes + heals were completed.  <br>
<br>
The moral of this is: please do not send a /tell to a Raid Leader or Assistant Raid Leader, unless you are designated as a Group Leader.  There are a number of things that we are doing, while you are waiting.  I did my best to juggle the tells, as well as make frequent /ooc announcements to let people know that I appreciated their patience.  I will communicate with all members on a raid through /ooc-- as well as Group Leaders if it is a general course of action.  /tell is used to give a specific direction to a group.  In extreme cases, /tell will be used to alert a group member that they will be xloc'd out if they continue to severely disrupt the progress of the raid, the safety of raid members, and most importantly... the overall enjoyment level of the majority of people involved.  That's what all of this is about for me-- if people die, they're not having fun.  I'm doing everything I can to prevent this.<br>
  <br>
   It follows that there are a few people who were on this raid that I have serious concerns about-- with regards to attitude, most importantly.  To these individuals, it seemed like they weren't having fun-- and they made this abundantly clear by abusing the /ooc channel (which was reserved for group leaders anyway), as well as /tell flooding Benadan and myself.  I will not publicly expose these people, I don't think that's right to do-- Raids are all about learning.  Warnings have been issues, from what I understand.  I think Kajira's post above is quite appropriate on this issue.  Please, I understand that everyone wants to get their loot, level, and have a great time doing it!  But it only takes a few negative people to spoil everyone's good time. I hope that shedding some light on WHAT Benadan and myself were doing defuses a bit of the mystery that surrounded our functions on this raid.  <br>
<br>
In order for &quot;/shout Epic Heroes rocks Kedge!&quot;, we need to function as a well-oiled machine-- any rust that the water has created along the way must be dealt with before we head back in.  If not, our ability to function will grind to a halt.<br>
<br>
Lasalle<br>
